  "diary": "Woke up to perfect weather and decided to make it a proper lazy Monday. Grabbed my usual cappuccino from the Starbucks near home, then settled in for the World Cup match—USA vs Wales had me glued to the screen through halftime. Something about a sunny June morning and international football just hits right. After lunch, I couldn't resist the weather anymore, so I headed out to Marymoor Park for a walk. The trails were gorgeous, and I needed to clear my head after staring at screens all morning. By the time I got back, the match was over and I was in that perfect post-exercise zone. Made a decent dinner, then just hung out online with friends, gaming and chatting. Ended the day feeling oddly grounded—like I actually lived it instead of just letting it happen.",
  "thought_process": "I think I was craving balance today. The light rail closure didn't affect me since I'm local in Redmond, so there was this unusual freedom to just exist without transit stress. The World Cup match felt like permission to be unproductive—everyone's watching, so why not me? But sitting through the full ninety minutes made me restless, which is why the park walk happened almost impulsively. I needed to move, to feel the sun, to remember I have a body. By evening, I was content in that low-key way where you're tired but satisfied. No big ambitions, just... a day that felt complete because I let it flow instead of forcing it.",
